==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Stockade
<hw>Stock*ade"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>estacade</ets> stockade, boom (confused in French with
<ets>estocade</ets>; see 1st <er>Stoccado</er>); fr. It.
<ets>steccata</ets> a palisade (influenced by OF. <ets>estach</ets>,
<ets>estaque</ets>, a stake, post), or from Sp. <ets>estacada</ets> a
palisade; both of German origin, and akin to E. <ets>stake</ets>,
<ets>stick</ets>; cf. G. <ets>stecken</ets> stick, OHG.
<ets>steccho</ets>. See <er>Stake</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, <er>Stick</er>,
<pos>n.</pos> & <pos>v. t.</pos>, and cf. <er>Estacade</er>,
<er>Stacket</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <def>A line of
stout posts or timbers set firmly in the earth in contact with each
other (and usually with loopholes) to form a barrier, or defensive
fortification.</def> <altsp>[Written also
<asp>stoccade</asp>.]</altsp>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An inclosure, or pen, made with posts and
stakes.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stockade</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Stockade
<hw>Stock*ade"</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Stockaded</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Stockading</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To surround, fortify, or
protect with a stockade.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stock-blind</ent>⟦br⟧
